The paper deals with consensus algorithms, which are typically studied in the Distributed Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The use of randomized algorithms and message complexity suggests that it could also be relevant to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The fact that the algorithms are designed to tolerate Byzantine faults suggests that it could be relevant to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category. The use of common coins and message broadcasts suggests that it could also be relevant to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Finally, the optimization techniques used in the algorithms suggest that it could be relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
